<subSubSection id="C358655E86186B3EFEFB881AFBA9FA4C" pageId="10" pageNumber="73" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586186B3EFEFB881AFBA9FA4C" blockId="10.[241,1224,1086,1495]" pageId="10" pageNumber="73">
Remarks. This species is extremely rare and small in size; a total of seven specimens have been recovered from the 
<typeStatus id="54F9887786186B3EFE6A88BEFE60FB69" box="[434,506,1226,1266]" pageId="10" pageNumber="73">type</typeStatus>
locality, including four specimens in previous investigations (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD34B2486186B3EFD7B888CFCF9FA84" author="Yoo, E. K." box="[675,867,1272,1311]" pageId="10" pageNumber="73" pagination="233 - 264" refId="ref27552" refString="Yoo, E. K., 1988. Early Carboniferous Mollusca from Gundy, Upper Hunter, New South Wales. Records of the Australian Museum 40 (4): 233 - 264." type="journal article" year="1988">Yoo, 1988</bibRefCitation>
). The shells exhibit perfectly balanced adult forms with a sharp boundary between protoconch and teleoconch. This species differs from the 
<typeStatus id="54F9887786186B3EFE4B89F6FE41FA31" box="[403,475,1410,1450]" pageId="10" pageNumber="73">type</typeStatus>
species O. 
<emphasis id="B936EAC786186B3EFD7A89F6FC9CFA31" box="[674,774,1410,1450]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="73">physa</emphasis>
Lindstrom in being much smaller in size and in lacking ornamentation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
